I don&#x27;t think @NotNull/@Nullable go away completely, but the use of optional makes dealing with nullables much easier. I think this is a much cleaner ways to deal with possible nulls:<p><pre><code>    public ImmutableMap<String, Long> getSessionTime(HttpServletRequest request) {
      return Optional.ofNullable(request.getSession(false))
        .map(s -> ImmutableMap.of(&quot;lastAccessedTime&quot;, s.getLastAccessedTime()))
        .orElseThrow(IllegalStateException::new);
    }
</code></pre>
If/When HttpServletRequest is updated to support Optional it can return it directly instead of the caller having to do it, and that is when Java will really see the upside.
